## Origin

Distilled from recurring manual-reviewer feedback patterns:

- §11 (Doc-06 crash-safety) — surfaced repeatedly when a runtime flake leaves `/logs/verifier/reward.txt` unwritten and the platform synthesises a "verifier did not run" row.
- §12 (difficulty alignment) — flagged across multiple reviews where the `-medium` / `-hard` directory suffix, `task.toml difficulty` field, test-suite docstring, and time-estimate fields disagreed in pairs or triples.
- §13 (task.toml field completeness) — first observed when a missing `[environment].workdir` field combined with a `difficulty` mismatch produced two independent rejection signals in one review pass. Later expanded after the platform also began enforcing `[environment].allow_internet` (literally `false`) with the BUILD-phase message `Missing required field: environment.allow_internet (must be false)`. The lesson generalises: every field the validator parses needs to be present AND consistent with the other four artifacts that mirror it.
- §14 (no runtime installs in `tests/test.sh`) — added after the May 2026 platform announcement that introduced `allow_internet = false` as a runtime guarantee, not just a task.toml flag. The old V2 canonical test.sh (`apt-get install -y curl` + `curl … | sh` + `uvx -p 3.13 -w pytest pytest …`) is now a hard failure on three axes: the static checker flags the forbidden calls, the runtime network is blocked so the curl hangs, and Doc-06 still expects `/logs/verifier/reward.txt` to exist. All three are repaired by moving deps into `environment/Dockerfile` and shrinking `tests/test.sh` to a `python -m pytest` invocation.
- §7 (difficulty bands rewrite) — replaced the simple `≤20% / 21-80% / >80%` thresholds with the May 2026 ordered HARD → MEDIUM → EASY classifier (best-model condition first, then worst-model fallback). The motivating change: a task where the best model scores 100% used to read as "easy" under the simple band even when the worst model scored 20%; under the new bands it correctly classifies as HARD via condition #2.
